    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1895-01-21T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1895-01-21T00:00:00-05:00" n="169"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d169">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Gresham</persName> to Mr. <persName
                            type="to">Gray</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1895-01-21">
                            <hi rend="italic">January 21, 1895</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>The terms of Mexico’s demand upon Guatemala have been obtained from the ministers
                    of both countries here. The fact that the present controversy is related to, if
                    not the outgrowth of, the boundary treaty of 1882 between Mexico and Guatemala,
                    the conclusion of which was largely due to the mediation of the United States,
                    constrains the President to express the earnest hope that the two neighboring
                    States will omit no means of reaching a direct settlement of their differences,
                    and failing in that refer them to friendly arbitration. The President is
                    unwilling to believe that Mexico contemplates a precipitate resort to <pb
                        facs="0254" n="988" xml:id="pg_988"/> arms. By their example the United
                    States have contributed to the establishment of the principle of arbitration,
                    and, in the President’s judgment, Mexico can not assume the responsibility of
                    disregarding the moral obligation to assist in extending the beneficent
                    influence of this principle, especially on the American continent.</p>
                <p>You will immediately communicate to the minister of foreign affairs the substance
                    of this instruction, leaving with him a copy if desired.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gresham.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
